{{About|an economic system based on decentralized decision-making and planning|economies that utilize [[central planning]]|Command economy}} {{Economic systems sidebar|By coordination}} {{Libertarian socialism|Economics}}
A '''decentralized-planned economy''' or '''decentrally-planned economy''' (occasionally '''[[Horizontalidad|horizontally]]-planned economy''') is a type of [[economic system]] based on [[Decentralization|decentralized]] [[economic planning]], in which decision-making is distributed amongst various economic agents or localized within production units. Decentralized planning is held in contrast to [[centralized planning]] where economic information is aggregated and used to formulate a plan for production, investment and resource allocation by a central authority. Decentralised planning can take shape both in the context of a [[mixed economy]] as well as in a [[Post-capitalism|post-capitalist]] economic system.
This usually implies some form of democratic decision-making within the economy or within firms in the form of [[economic democracy]] or [[industrial democracy]]. Alternatively, computer-based or computer-managed forms of decentralized coordination between economic enterprises have been proposed by various economists and computer scientists.{{citation needed|reason=for instance?|date=March 2016}}
Recent proposals for decentralized-economic planning have used the term "[[Participatory economics|participatory planning]]" to highlight the cooperative and democratic character of this system and to contrast it with centralized planning associated with the former [[Soviet Union]]. Proponents present decentralized and participatory economic planning as an alternative to [[market socialism]] for a post-capitalist society.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.umass.edu/dmkotz/What_Ec_Struc_Soc_08_03.pdf |title='&#39;What economic structure for socialism?'&#39;, by Kotz, David. 2008 |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2012-09-12}}</ref>
Decentralized-planning has been proposed as a basis for [[socialism]] and has been advocated by [[democratic socialist]]s and [[anarchists]] who advocate a non-market form of socialism while rejecting [[Economy of the Soviet Union|Soviet-type central planning]]. Some writers (e.g. Robin Cox) have argued that decentralised planning allows for a spontaneously self-regulating system of stock control (relying solely on calculation in kind) to come about and that in turn decisively overcomes the objections raised by the economic calculation argument that any large scale economy must necessarily resort to a system of market prices.<ref>Schweickart, David. [http://orion.it.luc.edu/~dschwei/demsoc.htm ''Democratic Socialism'']. Encyclopedia of Activism and Social Justice (2006): "Virtually all (democratic) socialists have distanced themselves from the economic model long synonymous with 'socialism,' i.e. the Soviet model of a non-market, centrally-planned economy...Some have endorsed the concept of 'market socialism,' a post-capitalist economy that retains market competition, but socializes the means of production, and, in some versions, extends democracy to the workplace. Some hold out for a non-market, participatory economy. All democratic socialists agree on the need for a democratic alternative to capitalism."</ref>
==Models==
===Cybernetics=== The use of computers to coordinate production in an optimal fashion has been proposed for socialist economies. The economist [[Oskar Lange]] argued that the computer is more efficient than the market process at solving the multitude of simultaneous equations required for allocating economic inputs efficiently (either in terms of physical quantities or monetary prices).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.calculemus.org/lect/L-I-MNS/12/ekon-i-modele/lange-comp-market.htm |title="The Computer and the market", Lange, Oskar. Retrieved March 16, 2011 |publisher=Calculemus.org |date= |accessdate=2012-09-12}}</ref>
The 1970 Chilean computer-controlled planned economy [[Project Cybersyn]] was pioneered by [[Salvador Allende]]'s socialist government in an attempt to move towards decentralised economic planning with the [[Viable system model|experimental viable system model]] of computed organisational structure of autonomous operative units though an [[algedonic feedback|algedonic feedback setting]] and bottom-up participatory decision-making by the [https://web.archive.org/web/20110512062330/http://www.cybersyn.cl:80/ingles/cybersyn/cyberfolk.html Cyberfolk] component.
===Negotiated coordination=== Economist [[Pat Devine]] has created a model of decentralized economic planning called "negotiated coordination", which is based upon social ownership by those affected by the use of the assets involved, with decisions made by those at the most localised level of production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gesd.free.fr/devine.pdf |title=Participatory Planning Through Negotiated Coordination |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref>
===Participatory Planning=== {{See also|Parecon}} The planning structure of a decentralized planned economy is generally based on a consumers council and producer council (or jointly, a distributive cooperative), which is sometimes called a [[consumers' cooperative]]. Producers and consumers, or their representatives, negotiate the quality and quantity of what is to be produced. This structure is central to [[participatory economics]], [[guild socialism]] and [[Anarchist economics|economic theories]] related to [[social anarchism|anarchism]].
==Similar concepts in practice==
===Decentralised planning in Kerala (India)=== {{Main|People's Planning in Kerala}} {{See also|District planning in India}} Some decentralised participation in economic planning has been implemented in various regions and states in India, most notably in [[People's Planning in Kerala|Kerala]]. Local level planning agencies assess the needs of people who are able to give their direct input through the Gram Sabhas (village-based institutions) and the planners subsequently seek to plan accordingly.
===Community participatory planning=== {{Main|Participatory planning}} The United Nations has developed local projects that promote participatory planning on a community level. Members of communities take decisions regarding [[community development]] directly.
==Political advocacy== Decentralised planning has been a feature of [[socialist]] and [[anarchist economics]]. Variations of decentralized planning include [[participatory economics]], [[economic democracy]] and [[industrial democracy]] and have been promoted by various political groups, most notably [[libertarian socialist]]s, [[guild socialism|guild socialists]], [[Libertarian Marxism|Libertarian Marxists]], [[Trotskyism|Trotskyists]]<ref>''Writings, 1932–33'' p. 96, Leon Trotsky.</ref>, [[anarchist]]s and [[democratic socialist]]s.
During the [[Spanish Revolution of 1936|Spanish Revolution]], some areas where anarchist and libertarian socialist influence through the [[Confederación Nacional del Trabajo|CNT]] and [[Unión General de Trabajadores|UGT]] was extensive, particularly rural regions, were run on the basis of decentralised planning resembling the principles laid out by [[Diego Abad de Santillan]] in the book ''After the Revolution''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://membres.multimania.fr/anarchives/site/syndic/aftertherevolution.htm#local |title=After the Revolution |publisher=Membres.multimania.fr |date=1936-01-07 |accessdate=2012-09-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829175011/http://membres.multimania.fr/anarchives/site/syndic/aftertherevolution.htm |archivedate=2012-08-29 |df= }}</ref>
